04441nam a22007575i 9780801460791DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014607917 a10.7591/97808014607912doi  a(DE-B1597)480059  a(OCoLC)979743945  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD5724b.L276 2016 7aBUS0970002bisacsh04a331.1379732231 aLane, Carrie M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Company of One :bInsecurity, Independence, and the New World of White-Collar Unemployment /cCarrie M. Lane. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b5 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Fortitude, Faith, and the Free Market -- t1. Silicon Prairie -- t2. A Company of One -- t3. The Hardest Job You’ll Ever Have -- t4. Rituals of Unemployment -- t5. Man Enough to Let My Wife Support Me -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeing laid off can be a traumatic event. The unemployed worry about how they will pay their bills and find a new job. In the American economy's boom-and-bust business cycle since the 1980s, repeated layoffs have become part of working life. In A Company of One, Carrie M. Lane finds that the new culture of corporate employment, changes to the job search process, and dual-income marriage have reshaped how today's skilled workers view unemployment. Through interviews with seventy-five unemployed and underemployed high-tech white-collar workers in the Dallas area over the course of the 2000s, Lane shows that they have embraced a new definition of employment in which all jobs are temporary and all workers are, or should be, independent "companies of one."Following the experiences of individual jobseekers over time, Lane explores the central role that organized networking events, working spouses, and neoliberal ideology play in forging and reinforcing a new individualist, pro-market response to the increasingly insecure nature of contemporary employment. She also explores how this new perspective is transforming traditional ideas about masculinity and the role of men as breadwinners. Sympathetic to the benefits that this "company of one" ideology can hold for its adherents, Lane also details how it hides the true costs of an insecure workforce and makes collective and political responses to job loss and downward mobility unlikely.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDisplaced workerszUnited States. 0aUnemployedzUnited States. 0aWhite collar workerszUnited States. 4aGender Studies. 4aLabor History. 4aSocial Work. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Workplace Culture.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146079140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801460791423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801460791/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK